## What happened

**Apple's Security framework has never natively supported DSA.** In earlier .NET versions on macOS, `DSA.Create()` was backed by an OpenSSL shim. Microsoft has been progressively deprecating legacy crypto algorithms, and in .NET 11 they removed (or stopped shipping) the OpenSSL-based DSA interop on macOS, causing `DSA.Create()` to throw `PlatformNotSupportedException`.

Linux still works because it links against the system's OpenSSL (which still supports DSA). Windows uses CNG, which also still supports DSA.

## How to fix it

**Option A — Use BouncyCastle for verification (recommended if you must keep DSA):**

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

public bool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] data, byte[] signature, DsaPublicKeyParameters pubKey)
{
    var signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA1withDSA");
    signer.Init(forSigning: false, pubKey);
    signer.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
    return signer.VerifySignature(signature);
}
```

This is pure managed code — no platform crypto dependency.

**Option B — Migrate to ECDSA or RSA (long-term):**

If you control both signing and verification, re-sign with a modern algorithm. DSA is considered legacy and will only get harder to use going forward.

**Option C — Runtime guard (if you want graceful degradation):**

```csharp
if (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
{
    using var dsa = DSA.Create();
    // ...
}
else
{
    // fall back to BouncyCastle
}
```

**Recommendation:** Go with BouncyCastle — it gives you a single cross-platform code path and removes the platform-specific branching entirely.
